data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort` kills a thread exceeding a time limit. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone.

### Problems in the original code

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),  // Overload for non-cancellable delegates
            timeout);
    }

    // Preferred overload — work cooperates with cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws on timeout even if the inner task is still running
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)`** — the CTS auto-cancels after the deadline. No forcible thread kill.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` catch → `OperationCanceledException` catch** — cooperative cancellation throws `OperationCanceledException`, not `ThreadAbortException`.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — no equivalent needed; cancellation is checked voluntarily.
4. **`new Thread(...)` → `Task.Run`** — uses the thread pool; `Task.WaitAsync` (.NET 6+) provides cancellable waiting.
5. **`using var cts`** — `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timers.

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|------------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** — if `work` never checks the token, it keeps running silently after timeout | Provide the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload and insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside long-running work |
| **Fire-and-forget task leak** — the timed-out `Task.Run` still occupies a thread pool thread until `work` finishes naturally | For truly uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`; the timer-based constructor allocates an internal timer |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`) |

### Example caller migration

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveWork(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// After (.NET 8) — cooperative version (preferred)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token =>
    {
        foreach (var item in items)
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
            Process(item);
        }
        return ComputeResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

The non-cancellable `Func<T>` overload still works as a drop-in replacement, but the timeout only prevents *waiting* — the abandoned work continues on a thread pool thread until it finishes naturally. Prefer passing the token through for true cancellation.
